# 1. Managers Don’t Care About LMS Metrics

You repeatedly rejected typical LMS dashboards:

* completion rate
* pass rate
* average grade
* training statistics

You see those as **corporate vanity metrics**.

What managers actually want is:

**People visibility.**

They want to know instantly:

• Who are my new hires
• Who is behind on training
• Who finished their training
• Who is struggling
• Who is crushing it

The dashboard is therefore:

**People-first, not course-first.**

---

# 2. The Dashboard Should Have Two Primary Views

You naturally converged on a **two-tab system**.

### Tab 1 — People (Primary)

This is the **default view**.

Managers immediately see employees.

Example sections:

**New Hires**

```
Alejandra – Server – Server101 – 30%  
Carlos – Server – Server101 – Not Started  
Maria – Host – Host101 – 60%
```

**Needs Attention**

```
Jose – Server – Failed Wine Quiz
Diana – Host – Training overdue
```

**Top Performers**

```
Alejandra – 96
Laura – 91
```

This answers the **manager's real question:**

> "Where are my people at?"

---

### Tab 2 — Courses (Secondary)

This is a **course management view**.

Managers can see:

* Server 101
* Wine Knowledge
* Steak Temps
* Cocktail Basics

And see:

```
22 enrolled
18 completed
4 in progress
```

But this is **secondary**, because managers care about **people**, not courses.

---

# 3. Onboarding Must Be Frictionless

You correctly pointed out something extremely important.

Managers will **not manually enroll employees**.

Your onboarding philosophy:

**Managers give a link.**

Example:

```
"Download the training app and enroll in Server 101."
```

The system automatically detects:

* new employees
* course enrollments
* progress

So the **system identifies new hires automatically**.

No HR workflow required.

